<div><h3>IDND 023 - Writing: Dream Logic and the Truth </h3>  <p><hr><div>
<p>When you tell a story, do you exaggerate or change details in order to express more clearly the way the situation felt? When you try to describe your dreams do you find yourself saying things like, &#8220;it was my house, but it wasn&#8217;t my house,&#8221; or &#8220;he was a combination of two people,&#8221;? In this course, we&#8217;ll look at dream logic and other oblique and mind-altering strategies writers use to communicate situations where two opposing truths exist at once, or an emotional truth differs from &#8220;facts.&#8221; Texts will feature fever dreams, child narrators, drugs, and other indirect ways writers look at difficult subjects in order to communicate the Truth more directly.</p>
</div>

